The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                                      HC issues notice against tour  Madurai: The Madurai bench of the Madras High Court on Tuesday issued a notice to secretaries of home, external affairs and youth and sports welfare on a PIL, seeking to stop the Indian cricket team from visiting Sri Lanka to play the triangular series at Colombo from September 8.  The petitioner, advocate Joel Poul Antony, referred to alleged human rights violations against Tamils by the Sri Lankan government, despite several appeals from the international community and asked India to support the same.  Voges in  Calcutta: Adam Voges Tuesday replaced injured wicket-keeper Brad Haddin, who is nursing a fractured finger, for Australia rsquo;s seven-match ODI series against England starting at the Oval on September 4.  Bari appointed  Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board on Tuesday appointed former Test captain Wasim Bari as its acting chief operating officer after the governing council signed a summary for the dismissal of Saleem Altaf.  Akhtar apology  Karachi: Controversial pacer Shoaib Akhtar has apologised to the PCB for violating his central contract by appearing on a television talk show. The Board has now sought the opinion of its legal advisor on the notice sent to Akhtar after the bowler made it clear that he had no intention of challenging the authority of the PCB or acting against its wishes.  Eduardo ban  Nyon: The Uefa has banned Arsenal striker Eduardo da Silva for two Champions League matches for diving to earn a penalty in a qualifying match against Celtic. Uefa rsquo;s disciplinary panel made the ruling Tuesday after a teleconference.  Barca win  Barcelona: Zlatan Ibrahimovic scored on his debut Monday as Barcelona began their Spanish league title defence with a 3-0 victory over Sporting Gijon. The Sweden striker dived low in the 82nd minute to head in Daniel Alves rsquo; deflected cross to round out the scoring.  Table tennis  New Delhi: Indian junior table tennis teams proved their mettle at the Taiyuan International Junior and Cadet Open, securing second position on the points table below China and bagging a gold medal in the under-18 boys rsquo; event.  Baljit update  New Delhi: Injured Indian hockey goalkeeper Baljit Singh on Tuesday said he can now identify colours after undergoing laser treatment to his right eye, which was injured during a practice session in Pune.  Kabaddi league  Chandigarh: The Punjab state government Tuesday announced that it would hold a World Kabaddi League next year with a whopping winner rsquo;s purse of Rs 1 crore.  
